[
  {
    "num": 1,
    "title": "Unclaimed Maturity & Survival Benefits",
    "sections": {
      "Hero Section": "Page headline: Recover Unclaimed Insurance Maturity and Survival Benefits\nSubheadline: If a policy matured, a money-back payout fell due, or an insurance amount should have reached you but did not, Sahirasta helps you understand the issue, organise the records, and move the matter toward release.\nSupport line: We assist policyholders, widows, legal heirs, families, senior citizens, and NRIs dealing with old LIC or private-insurer policies, missing paperwork, outdated bank details, or legacy record problems.\nPrimary CTA: Request a Case Review\nSecondary CTA: See Documents Usually Required",
      "What Is This Service?": "This service is for cases where an insurance amount became payable but never actually reached the right person. The policy may have matured long ago, a survival benefit may have fallen due under a money-back plan, or the insurer may have processed the amount but payment failed, remained unclaimed, or could not be completed because the records were outdated or incomplete.\nAn unpaid insurance amount is not always dramatic. Sometimes the issue is a missing discharge form, an old address, a bank account that no longer exists, or a policy that sat quietly in the background while the family assumed everything had already been handled. In other cases, the policyholder died, papers were scattered, and no one knows whether any maturity or survival amount was still pending.\nThis page is not about selling new insurance. It is about tracing, clarifying, and moving forward on amounts that should already have been paid under an existing policy.",
      "When Does This Issue Usually Arise?": "A policy matured years ago and the policyholder never received the maturity proceeds.\nA money-back or survival benefit was due but no credit ever appeared in the bank account.\nThe insurer sent a cheque that was never received, not encashed, or returned unpaid.\nThe policyholder changed address, bank account, contact number, or KYC details and the insurer could not complete payment.\nA family finds policy papers after a death and is unsure whether any maturity or survival amount is still pending.\nThe records are old enough that nobody is certain whether the amount was paid, reversed, kept in an unclaimed pool, or blocked by a mismatch.",
      "Who Typically Needs Help With This?": "Policyholders with old LIC or private-insurer policies that have matured or should have paid periodic benefits.\nSenior citizens who hold legacy policies with outdated servicing records.\nWidows, children, or other family members reviewing older insurance papers after a death.\nNRIs handling Indian insurance policies from abroad.\nFamilies that have partial information — a policy number, a bond, a receipt, or a premium trail — but no clear view of what is still payable.",
      "How Sahirasta Helps": "Sahirasta starts by separating three different possibilities that people often confuse: whether the policy genuinely reached a payout stage, whether the amount was already paid, and whether the real problem is not the benefit itself but a servicing or entitlement blockage.\nOnce that basic classification is clear, the practical work usually involves reviewing policy details, checking available records, identifying whether the issue is maturity, survival benefit, bank/KYC mismatch, nominee or legal-heir complication, or insurer-side record friction, and then preparing the right follow-up path.\nIn straightforward cases, the problem is often last-mile servicing: old bank details, missing discharge requirements, or broken communication. In more difficult cases, the issue becomes record reconstruction, entitlement proof, or confirmation of whether the amount is actually still outstanding.\nSahirasta helps clients organise the file, identify what is missing, understand what the insurer is likely to ask for, and move the case toward release with a more disciplined approach than ad hoc chasing.",
      "Documents Usually Required": "The exact document set depends on the policy, the insurer, and whether the policyholder is alive, deceased, or being represented by a family member. Commonly relevant documents include:\nPolicy bond, policy number, premium receipt, or any available insurer correspondence.\nIdentity and address proof of the policyholder or claimant.\nPAN, KYC, and bank proof, including cancelled cheque, where payout has to be re-routed.\nClaim or discharge forms if the insurer requires them for the type of payout involved.\nDeath certificate and proof of entitlement where the original policyholder is deceased.\nNominee records, legal-heir documents, succession papers, or relationship proof where the claim route is not straightforward.\nOverseas identity and address support where the claimant is an NRI.\nIt is better to begin with the papers available than to wait for a perfect file. Many cases become clearer only after the first round of review.",
      "Why These Cases Stay Unpaid or Get Stuck": "Older insurance payouts often remain unresolved for reasons that are more boring than people expect, but no less frustrating. The most common problems are outdated bank details, returned cheques, unsubmitted discharge requirements, old addresses, missing contact updates, or policyholder records that no longer match current identity documents.\nIn family cases, the difficulty grows when a policyholder has died and the family is not sure whether the issue is a maturity amount, a survival benefit, a death claim, or a record mismatch. The paperwork may not clearly state the current status, and the insurer may not act until the claimant route is clear.\nSome cases also stall because the policyholder or family assumes that the insurer will automatically push the money through. That is not always how it works. A payable amount may still sit unresolved if the insurer lacks updated bank details, completed servicing forms, or a clear claimant.",
      "Special Notes for Widows, Legal Heirs, and NRIs": "Many unresolved insurance matters surface only when a widow, son, daughter, or other family member begins sorting old documents after a death. The immediate question is often not legal theory but practical confusion: was this policy already paid, is something still due, and who is the right person to pursue it?\nNRIs often face an added layer of difficulty because the policy, branch, or claimant records are in India while the person handling the matter is abroad. That can mean more identity documentation, more coordination, and more dependence on well-organised paperwork, but it does not automatically make the case impossible.\nIn both family and NRI situations, incomplete papers do not automatically end the matter. They simply change the route. The real task is to work out whether the case is a payout trace, a servicing correction, an entitlement issue, or a combination of all three.",
      "Frequently Asked Questions": "How do I know whether a maturity or survival amount is still unpaid?\nThe starting point is to identify the policy status, due date, and whether any payment trail exists. Sometimes the amount is still unresolved; sometimes it was processed but never reached the right account; and sometimes the real problem is a records mismatch.\nWhat if I do not have the original policy bond?\nThe lack of the original bond does not automatically end the case. Other records such as policy numbers, receipts, insurer letters, or claimant identity documents may still help rebuild the file.\nCan family members pursue an unpaid maturity amount after the policyholder has died?\nYes, but the route may shift into nominee or legal-heir territory depending on the facts and the insurer’s requirements.\nCan NRIs pursue old Indian insurance payouts?\nYes. Additional documentation may be needed, but many cases can still be handled through a structured remote process.\nWhat if I am not even sure whether the amount is still outstanding?\nThat uncertainty is common. A realistic review often begins with exactly that question.",
      "Final Call to Action": "If an insurance policy matured, a survival benefit was due, or an amount seems to have disappeared into old records, waiting rarely improves the file. Addresses change, bank details go stale, branches move, and family knowledge fades.\nWhether you have a full set of papers or only partial information, Sahirasta can review the case and help you understand the next practical step.\nRequest a Case Review"
    },
    "slug": "insurance-unclaimed-maturity-survival-benefits"
