    "num": 2,
    "title": "Death Claim Support",
    "sections": {
      "Hero Section": "Page headline: Get Support With Insurance Death Claims\nSubheadline: When a policyholder has died and the claim process feels unclear, delayed, or blocked, Sahirasta helps families, widows, legal heirs, and NRIs organise the case and move it forward with practical clarity.\nSupport line: We assist in understanding the likely route, identifying missing documents, and reducing the confusion that often follows a death-related insurance claim.\nPrimary CTA: Request a Case Review\nSecondary CTA: See Documents Usually Required",
      "What Is This Service?": "This service is for cases where an insurance amount may become payable after the death of the policyholder and the family needs help understanding how to proceed. In some cases the route is straightforward because the nominee details are clear and the insurer’s records are in order. In many others, the file is messier: there may be more than one possible claimant, outdated records, missing papers, uncertainty about policy status, or confusion about what the insurer is actually asking for.\nA death claim is not only a paperwork issue. Families are often dealing with grief, incomplete financial information, and pressure to make sense of old records quickly. Sahirasta’s role is to bring order to the situation, help identify the likely claim route, and support the family through the practical steps needed to move the matter forward.\nThis page is not about selling insurance or giving emotional slogans. It is about helping families handle a difficult claim situation with structure, seriousness, and realistic expectations.",
      "When Does This Issue Usually Arise?": "A spouse, parent, or other family member dies and the family discovers an insurance policy but does not know how to make the claim.\nThe nominee is recorded, but the paperwork is incomplete or the insurer asks for additional clarification.\nNo nominee was registered, the nominee has also died, or the family is unsure who is legally entitled to proceed.\nThe insurer raises questions about policy status, premium payment history, assignment, loan, or other record issues before processing the claim.\nThe claimant is abroad, the family is spread across locations, or the branch that issued the policy is different from where the family is now trying to follow up.",
      "Who Typically Needs Help With This?": "Widows, widowers, sons, daughters, and other close family members trying to process an insurance claim after a death.\nLegal heirs where the nominee route is unclear, disputed, outdated, or unavailable.\nFamilies handling older LIC or private-insurer policies with incomplete records.\nNRIs dealing with Indian insurance claims remotely after the death of a parent, spouse, or relative.\nClients who have partial documents but do not know whether the issue is a simple death claim, a nominee problem, a record mismatch, or a wider succession issue.",
      "How Sahirasta Helps": "Sahirasta begins by clarifying what kind of case this actually is. That matters because families often describe everything as a death claim even when the real bottleneck lies elsewhere — for example, missing nominee records, policy loan complications, old servicing mismatches, or legal-heir documentation.\nOnce the basic route is identified, the practical work usually involves reviewing available papers, mapping the insurer’s likely document expectations, identifying gaps, and helping the claimant understand what can realistically be resolved through nominee documentation, branch-level servicing, or a more formal entitlement route.\nIn many cases, the family’s biggest problem is not the absence of all documents but the absence of a clean file. Sahirasta helps organise the case, reduce confusion, and support follow-up so the insurer’s queries can be handled more systematically.\nWhere the matter is genuinely complex, Sahirasta helps the family understand the complication early instead of giving false comfort. That saves time, reduces wasted effort, and makes the next steps clearer.",
      "Documents Usually Required": "The exact list depends on the insurer, the policy, the claim amount, the nominee position, and whether the matter is straightforward or disputed. Commonly relevant documents include:\nOriginal policy bond, policy number, premium receipts, or insurer correspondence.\nDeath certificate of the policyholder.\nIdentity and address proof of the claimant.\nBank proof of the claimant, including cancelled cheque or account details where payout is to be credited.\nNominee proof, relationship proof, or legal-heir documents, depending on how the claim must be established.\nPAN, KYC, and other servicing documents where required by the insurer.\nAdditional overseas identification or attestation support where the claimant is an NRI.\nFamilies should not wait for a perfect file before seeking clarity. In many death-claim cases, the first useful step is to understand what type of claim it is and what missing documents actually matter.",
      "Why These Cases Get Stuck or Delayed": "Death claims often slow down because families assume the existence of a policy automatically means an immediate payout. In reality, delays usually arise from entitlement questions, incomplete servicing records, mismatch in claimant details, missing policy papers, unclear nominee status, or insurer queries that are not answered in time.\nIn older policies, the problem may be buried in legacy records — a policy loan, an assignment, a change that was never properly updated, or a missing trail showing whether the policy was in force at the relevant time.\nSome cases also become harder because different family members hold different pieces of the puzzle. One person has the bond, another knows the premium history, another holds the death certificate, and nobody has a complete picture. That fragmentation causes avoidable delay.",
      "Special Notes for Widows, Legal Heirs, and NRIs": "Widows and immediate family members are often pushed into claim handling at a time when they are least prepared for bureaucratic complexity. A calm, structured review helps separate what is emotionally heavy from what is procedurally required.\nWhere there is no clear nominee route, the case may shift into legal-heir or succession territory. That does not make the claim impossible, but it does change the proof and process needed.\nNRIs often face additional difficulty because the policy and insurer records are in India while the claimant is abroad. Remote handling is still possible in many cases, but documentation and follow-up need to be better organised, not looser.",
      "Frequently Asked Questions": "Can a widow make the claim even if she is not sure whether she is the recorded nominee?\nPossibly, yes — but the first step is to establish what the insurer’s records show and whether the case can proceed through nominee status, legal-heir proof, or another entitlement route.\nWhat if the original policy bond is missing?\nThe claim may still be possible. Missing bonds create more work, but other records may help reconstruct the case and identify what the insurer will require.\nWhat if multiple family members are involved?\nThat is common. The key is to understand who is entitled to act, what documents support that position, and whether the insurer is likely to require additional family or succession documentation.\nCan an NRI pursue a death claim on an Indian policy?\nYes. Extra documentation may be required, but many cases can still be reviewed and progressed through a structured remote process.\nWhat if the insurer has already asked for documents and the case still is not moving?\nThat usually means the issue is not only submission but clarity. A careful review can help identify whether the real obstacle is entitlement, record mismatch, policy status, or incomplete follow-up.",
      "Final Call to Action": "If your family is trying to deal with an insurance claim after a death and the process feels unclear, slow, or harder than it should be, do not keep guessing your way through it.\nWhether you have a clear nominee record or only partial papers, Sahirasta can review the case and help you understand the likely path, the missing pieces, and the next practical steps.\nRequest a Case Review"
    },
