    "num": 5,
    "title": "Lost Policy Bond",
    "sections": {
      "Hero Section": "Page headline: Lost Your Policy Bond? We Help You Move the Claim or Service Process Forward\nSubheadline: A missing policy bond can delay maturity, surrender, loan, correction, or death-claim work. Sahirasta helps you identify the right duplicate-document route and organise the case properly.\nPrimary CTA: Request a Case Review\nSupport line: For policyholders, widows, legal heirs, NRIs, and families dealing with old LIC or insurance records.",
      "What This Service Is": "A lost policy bond does not always mean the underlying insurance policy is lost. In many cases, the policy still exists in the insurer’s records, but the original bond is missing, damaged, misplaced, or unavailable when the client finally needs to act. The problem usually becomes urgent only when someone tries to claim maturity proceeds, submit a death claim, apply for a policy loan, surrender the policy, or correct older records and is told that the original bond is not readily available.\nThis service focuses on helping the client move from panic to process. Sahirasta helps identify whether the insurer will need a duplicate policy bond, a lost-policy declaration, an indemnity-based route, or some other servicing step depending on the type of request and the insurer’s requirements. The aim is not to dramatise the missing paper, but to restore documentary control so the real financial issue can move forward.",
      "When This Issue Usually Arises": "The problem often surfaces after many years of inactivity, when the policyholder has shifted home, changed family circumstances, or simply not handled the policy file for a long time.\nIt also arises after the death of the policyholder, when widows, children, or other legal heirs discover that the family knows the insurer’s name or policy number but cannot find the original bond in the documents left behind.\nIn some cases the bond is not exactly lost, but damaged, partially illegible, or held by another family member, branch, or intermediary. In others, the client is unsure whether the bond was ever received, whether it was submitted earlier for some servicing step, or whether the policy is now in a form where the insurer can process the case without the original bond after additional paperwork.",
      "Who Typically Needs Help With This?": "Policyholders nearing maturity who need to submit documents but cannot locate the bond.\nFamilies and legal heirs handling a death claim where the policy papers are incomplete or scattered.\nSenior citizens dealing with very old LIC or insurer policies kept in paper files for decades.\nClients trying to surrender a policy, take a loan, or correct records after years of not engaging with the policy.\nNRIs and remote families who know that a policy exists but do not have direct physical access to the original documents in India.",
      "How Sahirasta Helps": "Sahirasta begins by identifying the real objective behind the missing bond. The question is not only whether the paper is lost, but what the client is actually trying to do: claim maturity, pursue a death claim, seek a policy loan, surrender the policy, correct records, or revive communication with the insurer. That distinction matters because insurers may not ask for the same replacement route in every situation.\nThe next step is to gather whatever evidence still exists: policy number, premium receipts, branch correspondence, old SMS or email alerts, bank entries, servicing letters, or any partial copy of the bond. Even incomplete evidence can help establish the policy trail and reduce guesswork. Sahirasta then helps organise the case so that the insurer sees a coherent request rather than a confused explanation that keeps bouncing between desks.\nWhere a duplicate bond or lost-policy declaration is required, the case must usually be supported with identity proof, policy particulars, claimant details, and any indemnity or declaration documents the insurer asks for. Sahirasta helps the client understand this stage clearly and prepares the file so the missing document does not keep blocking the real financial outcome.\nIf the issue is part of a larger death-claim or servicing problem, Sahirasta also helps separate the bond problem from the entitlement problem. Families often lose time because they are trying to solve every issue at once. A cleaner approach is to identify which missing paper can be replaced, which entitlement documents are still needed, and what the insurer is likely to insist on before moving the claim or service request.",
      "Documents Usually Required": "The exact requirements vary by insurer and the underlying service requested, but commonly relevant documents include:\nPolicy number and whatever policy details are available, including insurer name, branch, premium mode, or approximate commencement date.\nAny photocopy, scanned copy, image, schedule page, premium receipt, ECS record, bank entry, or servicing communication linked to the policy.\nIdentity and address proof of the policyholder or claimant.\nPAN, bank proof, and contact details where the next servicing step involves payment or proceeds.\nDeath certificate, nominee documents, legal-heir documents, or relationship proof where the policyholder has died.\nInsurer-prescribed declaration, indemnity, or duplicate-bond request forms where applicable.\nAny letters, emails, branch responses, or screenshots showing that the insurer has already indicated what is missing.",
      "Why These Cases Get Stuck When the Policy Bond Is Missing": "Many clients assume the missing bond is a small paperwork issue and approach the branch without a structured file. The result is repeated visits, inconsistent guidance, and requests for fresh documents each time.\nIn older policies, the contact details, signature, nominee details, or bank account linked to the policy may also be outdated. That means the lost bond is only one part of the blockage.\nSome families do not know the exact policy status. They may not know whether the policy matured already, lapsed, became paid-up, was assigned, or had a loan attached. Without clarity on status, the missing bond problem becomes harder to resolve.\nWhere the policyholder has died, the insurer may need to see both replacement-document steps and entitlement documents. These cases slow down further if family members are unclear about who should sign, who the nominee is, or whether succession documentation is required.",
      "Special Notes for Widows, Legal Heirs, and NRIs": "Widows and families often face this problem in emotionally difficult circumstances. They may know that a policy exists but feel paralysed because the original bond cannot be found. The right response is not to assume the claim is impossible, but to rebuild the document trail patiently and understand what the insurer will accept as the next step.\nNRIs face a different version of the same problem. The policy may be in India, the family may have partial papers, and branch communication may be fragmented. These cases can still move, but only if the records, claimant identity, and authority to act are organised properly from the start.\nA lost bond does not automatically destroy the claim. But it does increase the need for clean paperwork, correct declarations, and careful sequencing.",
      "Frequently Asked Questions": "Can a claim or policy service request move forward if the original policy bond is missing?\nOften yes, but the insurer may require a duplicate-bond request, declaration, indemnity, or other supporting process before proceeding.\nWhat if I only know the insurer name and have no policy bond?\nThat is still workable in some cases if other policy evidence exists, such as premium receipts, bank entries, SMS alerts, servicing letters, or old correspondence.\nCan a widow or family member handle this after the policyholder’s death?\nYes, but the missing-bond issue will usually need to be handled alongside nominee or legal-heir documentation, depending on the insurer’s record and claim stage.\nDoes losing the policy bond mean the money is gone?\nNo. The missing bond is a documentation problem, not proof that the policy benefit has vanished. The real question is how to re-establish the file correctly.\nCan NRIs address a lost policy-bond issue without repeated travel?\nMany cases can still be organised remotely, though paperwork and coordination may take longer when records are scattered across countries or family members.",
      "Final Call to Action": "If a missing policy bond is delaying maturity, surrender, correction, loan, or death-claim action, the next step is not panic. It is to identify what the insurer actually needs, what evidence still exists, and how to move the case in the right order.\nIf you cannot find the original policy bond and do not know how to proceed, Sahirasta can review the case and help you organise the replacement-document route properly.\nRequest a Case Review"
    },
    "slug": "insurance-lost-policy-bond"
  },
