    "num": 6,
    "title": "Nominee Issues",
    "sections": {
      "Hero Section": "Page headline: Nominee Problems Are Blocking the Insurance Claim? We Help Clarify the Route\nSubheadline: Insurance claims often get delayed because the nominee details are outdated, missing, disputed, or misunderstood. Sahirasta helps organise the entitlement position and move the case forward with the right supporting documents.\nPrimary CTA: Request a Case Review\nSupport line: For policyholders, widows, legal heirs, NRIs, and families handling old LIC or insurer records.",
      "What This Service Is": "A nominee issue is not always a simple clerical mistake. In some cases, there is no nominee recorded. In others, the nominee died earlier, the name on record does not match current ID documents, the family assumes the nominee is the final owner, or multiple relatives disagree about who should make the claim. The result is that the insurer does not get a clean entitlement file.\nThis service focuses on untangling that confusion. Sahirasta helps identify what kind of nominee problem exists, what the insurer is likely to ask for next, and whether the matter can proceed through a nominee route, a legal-heir route, or a broader succession-support route.",
      "When This Issue Usually Arises": "The problem usually surfaces after the death of the policyholder, when the family starts the claim process and discovers that the nomination details are old, incomplete, or practically unusable. A policy may still show a deceased nominee, a minor nominee without proper guardian details, or a nominee whose name does not match current records.\nIt also arises when a policyholder wants to update an old policy and realises that the nomination was never added, never changed after marriage or remarriage, or no longer reflects the present family situation. In some cases the family assumes that being the legal heir is enough, while the insurer first asks about the nomination on record.\nAnother common version is internal family confusion. One relative may have the bond, another may be named as nominee, and others may believe they also have rights in the proceeds. These cases become emotionally messy very quickly unless the paperwork is organised properly.",
      "Who Typically Needs Help With This?": "Widows, children, parents, or siblings trying to file a death claim where the nominee details are missing or problematic.\nFamilies dealing with old LIC or insurer policies where the nomination was never updated after major life events.\nClients facing mismatch between nominee name, relationship, age, or identity records.\nFamilies where the nominee is deceased, unreachable, unwilling to cooperate, or not the only interested party.\nNRIs and remote families handling nominee questions from outside India while documents remain scattered across relatives or old files.\nPolicyholders who want to correct the position before a future claim becomes more complicated.",
      "How Sahirasta Helps": "Sahirasta begins by separating the emotional dispute from the paperwork issue. The first question is what exactly the insurer’s records show: whether a nominee exists, whether that nominee is traceable and valid in practical terms, and whether the case can move on the basis of nomination alone or requires a broader entitlement file.\nThe next step is to gather the documents that establish the present position clearly. That may include the policy record, death certificate, identity and relationship proof, legal-heir documents where needed, and any prior correspondence that shows what the insurer has already asked for or objected to.\nWhere the nominee details are outdated or unusable, the case often turns into a documentation and sequencing problem rather than a purely legal one. Families lose time when they submit partial papers without a clear explanation of why the nominee route is not straightforward. Sahirasta helps organise the file so the insurer sees one coherent claim path instead of a bundle of disconnected documents.\nIn some cases the right route is straightforward. In others, the family may need succession proof, indemnities, declarations, guardian documents for a minor beneficiary, or additional internal clarifications. Sahirasta helps map that route before the family wastes time on repeated branch visits and contradictory advice.",
      "Documents Usually Required": "The exact document set depends on the insurer and the nature of the nominee issue, but commonly relevant documents include:\nPolicy number, policy schedule, bond, or any servicing communication showing the nominee details on record.\nDeath certificate of the policyholder where the issue arises in a death-claim context.\nIdentity, address, PAN, and bank proof of the nominee or claimant.\nRelationship proof and family documents where the insurer needs clarity on how the claimant relates to the policyholder.\nLegal-heir certificate, succession documents, affidavit, indemnity, or declaration where nomination alone does not resolve the entitlement question.\nDeath certificate of the nominee where the recorded nominee is no longer alive.\nGuardian documents where the nominee is or was a minor and representation is now required.\nAny branch letters, email trails, rejection notes, or document checklists already shared by the insurer.",
      "Why Nominee-Issue Cases Get Stuck": "Families often assume that the word nominee settles everything. In practice, nominee-related cases can stall because the nomination on the insurer’s record is missing, outdated, inconsistent with current identity documents, or no longer workable after death or family change.\nAnother common problem is that the family submits identity proof but does not explain the entitlement logic clearly. If the insurer cannot understand whether the claim is being made by the nominee, by legal heirs, or by a guardian or representative, the file keeps bouncing back for clarification.\nOlder policies create another layer of difficulty. The policyholder may have married, remarried, shifted cities, changed names in records, or never updated nomination at all. In such cases, the insurer may ask for additional proof before releasing any money.\nThese cases also get delayed because families disagree internally. One person may be coordinating, another may be named in the record, and others may challenge the route. Without a structured file, every round of communication becomes slower and more stressful.",
      "Special Notes for Widows, Legal Heirs, and NRIs": "Widows and children often face nominee issues at the worst possible time, when the death claim itself is emotionally heavy and the policy paperwork is scattered. A nomination problem does not automatically mean the money is lost, but it does mean the entitlement route needs to be explained properly.\nNRIs face an added burden because branch communication, notarisation, identity proof, and family coordination may happen across countries. These cases are still workable, but only if the documentation is arranged in the right order and the family is clear about who is claiming on what basis.\nIn some cases the nominee issue is only one part of a larger block involving a missing bond, outdated KYC, old address, policy loan, or insurer-record mismatch. The right strategy is to identify the primary blocker first and then sequence the rest properly.",
      "Frequently Asked Questions": "What if the policy has no nominee recorded?\nThe claim may still be possible, but the insurer will usually need a different entitlement route, often involving legal-heir or succession-related documents.\nWhat happens if the nominee recorded in the policy has already died?\nThe insurer will usually need supporting documents showing that the nominee is no longer alive and may then ask for the next valid entitlement route based on the case facts.\nDoes the nominee always become the final owner of the insurance money?\nNot every family dispute can be solved by quoting the nominee field alone. The practical route depends on the insurer’s process, the family situation, and the supporting documents available.\nCan Sahirasta help if the family itself is confused about who should claim?\nYes. Many cases first need the paperwork route clarified before the insurer can process anything sensibly.\nCan NRIs handle nominee-issue cases without repeated travel?\nMany cases can be organised remotely, though delays increase when documents are scattered across relatives, countries, or old insurer records.",
      "Final Call to Action": "If a policy claim is stuck because the nominee details are missing, outdated, disputed, or unclear, the next step is to organise the entitlement route properly. Guesswork only creates more delay.\nIf nominee confusion is blocking an insurance payout, Sahirasta can review the case and help identify the right document and claim path.\nRequest a Case Review"
    },
    "slug": "insurance-nominee-issues"
  },
