    "num": 8,
    "title": "Old LIC / Insurer Record Mismatch",
    "sections": {
      "Hero Section": "Page headline: Old LIC or Insurer Record Mismatch? We Help Untangle the File and Move It Forward\nSubheadline: When names, dates, policy details, branch records, or payout history do not match across old insurance records, Sahirasta helps identify the likely mismatch, organise the supporting papers, and structure the next steps.\nPrimary CTA: Request a Case Review\nSupport line: For policyholders, widows, legal heirs, NRIs, and families dealing with old LIC or insurer records that do not align.",
      "What This Service Is": "An insurer-record mismatch case arises when the policy papers, insurer system, claimant documents, or branch records do not line up cleanly. The problem may involve name spelling differences, changed surname after marriage, different initials, inconsistent dates of birth, old addresses, old bank details, nominee record gaps, policy-status confusion, or legacy branch entries that do not match the papers now being submitted.\nThese cases are especially common in older LIC and insurer files because the policy may have moved through multiple servicing stages over many years - manual records, branch transfers, migration to newer systems, family changes, and incomplete updates. By the time a maturity claim, death claim, survival benefit, or servicing request is made, one part of the record may say one thing and another part may say something else.\nThis service focuses on identifying what exactly does not match, why that mismatch matters to the insurer, and what route may be needed to correct, explain, or reconcile the file. The goal is not vague follow-up. The goal is to turn a confusing record problem into a structured documentation problem that can actually be worked.",
      "When This Issue Usually Arises": "A maturity, death claim, survival benefit, surrender, or servicing request is delayed because the insurer says the records do not match the documents submitted.\nThe policyholder's name appears differently across the policy bond, PAN, Aadhaar, bank records, marriage-related documents, or insurer database.\nThe date of birth, address, signature, or contact details in the insurer's old record do not match the current identity documents.\nA policy was serviced through an old branch, transferred to another office, or migrated from older records, and the current file history is incomplete or inconsistent.\nThe family is told that nominee details, claimant relationship details, or other core records do not align with what the insurer has on file.\nAn old payout, policy loan, assignment, or servicing remark appears in insurer records but is not clearly reflected in the papers available with the family.\nThe client has some policy documents, but the insurer system reflects a status, endorsement, or history that nobody is able to explain properly.",
      "Who Typically Needs Help With This?": "Policyholders whose old LIC or insurer policies are stuck because personal details in the record no longer match current documents.\nWidows, children, nominees, and legal heirs trying to pursue a claim where the insurer says that the old policy record is inconsistent or incomplete.\nFamilies handling older policies after a death and discovering that names, dates, nominee records, or branch history do not align cleanly.\nNRIs trying to manage Indian insurance matters remotely where the insurer's legacy records are difficult to verify from abroad.\nClients who have been told informally to 'correct the record first' but have never received a clear explanation of what exactly is wrong.",
      "How Sahirasta Helps": "Sahirasta begins by identifying the mismatch precisely. That step matters because 'record mismatch' is often used loosely. The actual issue may be a simple spelling variation, a name-change issue after marriage, an old address problem, a date-of-birth inconsistency, a branch-level record gap, an unupdated nominee trail, or a larger file-history problem involving multiple older entries.\nOnce the likely mismatch is identified, Sahirasta helps organise the papers into a coherent sequence so the problem can be explained instead of guessed. In many cases, the documents exist but are scattered and disconnected. One paper proves identity, another shows the old policy record, another explains the family relationship, and another helps reconcile the old and current details. Unless these are arranged properly, the insurer's objections keep repeating.\nWhere the matter overlaps with death claim, nominee issue, unpaid survival benefit, lost policy bond, or policy-loan complications, Sahirasta helps separate the issues so the file is not treated as one shapeless old-policy problem. That separation often makes the next step much clearer.",
      "Documents Usually Required": "The exact documents depend on the nature of the mismatch and the insurer involved, but commonly relevant papers include:\nPolicy bond, policy number, premium receipts, policy schedule, endorsement pages, and any old insurer or branch communication.\nPAN, Aadhaar, passport, bank proof, address proof, and any other identity documents showing the current record clearly.\nOlder identity or address proofs where they help connect the present details with the historical policy record.\nMarriage certificate, gazette publication, affidavit, name-change support, or relationship documents where surname or identity details changed over time.\nDeath certificate, nominee papers, legal-heir documents, succession-related papers, or claimant-relationship documents where the policyholder is deceased.\nBank statements, old cheque trail, or payout communication where the mismatch affects whether an amount was paid or who received it.\nAny insurer letters, emails, SMS alerts, branch notes, or objection memos showing what discrepancy the insurer has already flagged.",
      "Why These Cases Get Stuck": "Old-record mismatch matters drag on because the insurer usually wants consistency before moving money or servicing rights. If the name on the bond does not match the bank record, if the claimant's relationship is unclear on the face of the file, or if the policy history appears incomplete, the insurer will often slow the matter rather than take a clean decision quickly.\nAnother problem is that families often treat the issue as if one missing document will solve everything. In reality, the difficulty may be cumulative: part identity issue, part old branch-history issue, part nominee or entitlement confusion. Unless the mismatch is classified properly, repeated submissions only create more delay and more contradictory responses.\nThese cases also become harder with time. Records get older, branch staff change, papers go missing, and family memory becomes unreliable. What should have been a small clarification years earlier can become a full reconstruction exercise later.",
      "Special Notes for Widows, Legal Heirs, and NRIs": "Widows and family members often encounter insurer-record mismatch only after the policyholder's death, when the branch or claims desk starts pointing out name differences, old nominee gaps, address history problems, or document inconsistencies that were never resolved during the policyholder's lifetime.\nLegal heirs may face additional difficulty where the insurer is not only checking the claimant's entitlement but also trying to reconcile the policyholder's historical record. In such matters, the entitlement question and the record-correction question may move together, which is why the file has to be organised with more care than a simple servicing request.\nNRIs face an obvious coordination burden because the policy papers, family documents, older bank trail, and branch-level history may all remain in India while the person handling the matter is abroad. These cases can still be worked, but only with disciplined document sequencing and realistic expectations about old-record cleanup.",
      "Frequently Asked Questions": "What is an insurer-record mismatch in an insurance case?\nIt means the insurer's records do not align cleanly with the policy papers, identity documents, claimant documents, or servicing history now being relied on.\nWhat if the policyholder's name is spelled differently across documents?\nThat is common in older files. The key is not panic but proof - the records have to be connected through supporting documents so the insurer can see that the file still relates to the same person.\nCan a widow or legal heir continue the case if the old policy record is inconsistent?\nOften yes, but the file usually needs both entitlement documents and record-reconciliation documents. The insurer may not treat those as separate issues unless the case is structured properly.\nWhat if the branch says the old record is not traceable or not clear?\nThat does happen in older LIC and insurer matters. The practical route is usually to build the case from the available bond, policy number, receipts, claimant documents, and whatever historical communication still exists.\nCan NRIs handle old-record mismatch cases remotely?\nMany can, though older files often need stronger coordination, clearer documentation, and more patience than standard policy servicing matters.",
      "Final Call to Action": "If an insurance case is being delayed because the old LIC or insurer record does not match the documents now being produced, vague follow-up rarely fixes it. The mismatch has to be identified, explained, and supported properly.\nWhether the problem involves name differences, old branch records, identity mismatch, nominee confusion, or legacy data gaps, Sahirasta can review the file and help identify the likely route to move the matter forward.\nRequest a Case Review"
    },
    "slug": "insurance-old-record-mismatch"
