  {
    "num": 9,
    "title": "Survival Benefit Not Received",
    "sections": {
      "Hero Section": "Page headline: Survival Benefit Not Received? We Help Trace and Move the Case Forward\nSubheadline: If a money-back instalment or survival benefit under an insurance policy fell due but never reached you, Sahirasta helps review the records, identify the likely blockage, and organise the next steps.\nPrimary CTA: Request a Case Review\nSupport line: For policyholders, widows, legal heirs, NRIs, and families dealing with old LIC or insurer money-back policies.",
      "What This Service Is": "A survival-benefit issue arises when a scheduled payout under a money-back or similar policy became due, but the amount was never actually received by the policyholder. Unlike a final maturity claim, this problem concerns an intermediate payout that should have been released during the life of the policy and not only at the end of the term.\nThese cases are often more confusing than they sound. The family may know that the policy was supposed to pay something after a certain number of years, but may not know whether that instalment was processed, returned, held back for want of updated records, or never completed because the insurer’s servicing file was outdated. Sometimes the policyholder assumed the amount was small and would come automatically. Sometimes the cheque or credit failed and nobody followed up properly.\nThis service focuses on tracing that missed payout, distinguishing it from maturity and death-claim issues, and helping the client understand whether the real problem is non-receipt, policy status, bank/KYC mismatch, or old record friction.",
      "When This Issue Usually Arises": "The due date for a money-back instalment has passed, but no amount was ever credited to the policyholder’s bank account.\nThe insurer says a survival benefit was issued long ago, but the policyholder never received the cheque or cannot trace any bank credit.\nThe policyholder changed bank account, address, signature, contact number, or KYC details and the payout could not be completed properly.\nA family reviewing old policy papers realises that one or more periodic payouts may have become due before maturity, but there is no clear payment trail.\nThe policyholder later died, and the family is unsure whether an earlier survival benefit remained unpaid separately from any death claim or maturity-related amount.\nThe insurer’s records are old enough that nobody is clear whether the amount was paid, returned, kept pending, or blocked by a mismatch.",
      "Who Typically Needs Help With This?": "Policyholders holding money-back or similar policies where periodic benefits were supposed to be paid during the policy term.\nSenior citizens dealing with old LIC or insurer policies and trying to understand whether earlier payouts were ever received.\nWidows, children, or other family members sorting older insurance documents after a death and trying to identify unpaid amounts.\nNRIs handling Indian insurance policies remotely and trying to reconstruct whether a due survival benefit was missed.\nFamilies with only partial records such as a bond, policy number, premium trail, or old branch communication but no clear payout history.",
      "How Sahirasta Helps": "Sahirasta begins by identifying whether a survival benefit was actually due under the policy and on what basis. That sounds obvious, but many families mix up money-back instalments, maturity amounts, bonus expectations, and death-claim benefits as if they were all the same. They are not. The first job is to classify the amount correctly.\nThe next step is to examine whether the issue is true non-payment, failed payment, missing bank details, incomplete servicing compliance, or simple uncertainty because the payment trail was never preserved. In some cases the insurer may have attempted payment through cheque or older bank records. In others, the amount may still be unresolved because no updated discharge or banking documents were submitted when the instalment fell due.\nSahirasta helps organise the file, identify the likely blockage, and move the matter forward in a more disciplined way than scattered follow-up. Where the matter overlaps with nominee, death-claim, old-record mismatch, or missing-document problems, Sahirasta also helps separate those issues so the survival-benefit question does not remain buried under general confusion.",
      "Documents Usually Required": "The exact papers depend on the insurer, the age of the policy, and whether the policyholder is alive or represented by family. Commonly relevant documents include:\nPolicy bond, policy number, premium receipts, policy schedule, or any insurer communication showing the money-back or survival-benefit structure.\nIdentity, address, PAN, and bank proof of the policyholder or claimant.\nBank statements, cheque records, or any other payment trail that may help show whether the due amount was ever actually received.\nDischarge forms, servicing requests, or KYC updates where the insurer required these before release of the instalment.\nDeath certificate and entitlement documents where the policyholder is deceased and the family is now tracing the unpaid benefit.\nNominee, legal-heir, succession, relationship, or representative documents where the claimant route is not straightforward.\nOverseas identity and address support where the person handling the matter is an NRI.",
      "Why These Cases Get Stuck": "Survival-benefit cases often remain unresolved because the amount is neither dramatic enough to trigger urgent action nor obvious enough to track casually. A policyholder may miss a cheque, overlook a failed credit, or assume that the insurer will reprocess the amount automatically. That assumption is often wrong.\nAnother common problem is that old money-back policies sit in legacy servicing systems with outdated addresses, closed bank accounts, older signature records, or incomplete KYC. When the due instalment arises, the payout does not move cleanly, and years later nobody remembers what happened.\nThese matters also get confused with other insurance events. Families may think they are handling a maturity claim or a death claim when the unresolved issue is actually an earlier periodic benefit that fell due independently. Unless the timeline is reconstructed properly, the case stays muddy and the insurer’s responses remain fragmented.",
      "Special Notes for Widows, Legal Heirs, and NRIs": "Widows and family members often discover these issues only while sorting old papers after a death. The immediate question is usually not technical law but practical uncertainty: was a periodic benefit already paid, is it still traceable, and who should now pursue the matter if the original policyholder is no longer alive?\nWhere the policyholder died after a survival benefit had already fallen due, the family may need to distinguish between an unpaid instalment that belonged to the policyholder and a later death-claim or policy-status question. That distinction matters because the paperwork route may not be identical.\nNRIs face an added coordination burden because the policy records, old bank trail, and branch-level history may all remain in India while the person trying to understand the case is abroad. These matters are still workable, but only if the records are gathered patiently and the issue is defined correctly from the start.",
      "Frequently Asked Questions": "What is a survival benefit in an insurance policy?\nIn this context, it usually means a scheduled payout due during the policy term under a money-back or similar plan, rather than the final maturity amount at the end.\nWhat if I am not sure whether the survival benefit was ever paid?\nThat is common. The first step is to reconstruct the due date, check available bank or cheque trail, and compare it with the insurer’s records.\nCan a family pursue an unpaid survival benefit after the policyholder’s death?\nOften yes, but the route depends on whether the amount had already become due during the policyholder’s lifetime and how the claimant’s entitlement must now be established.\nWhat if I do not have the original policy bond?\nThe case may still be reviewed using other available records such as policy number, premium receipts, insurer letters, or claimant documents, though missing papers can slow the process.\nCan NRIs trace unpaid survival benefits on Indian policies?\nYes. Additional documentation and more careful coordination may be needed, but many such cases can still be handled through a structured remote process.",
      "Final Call to Action": "If a survival benefit under a money-back policy fell due but never reached the right person, leaving the file untouched rarely improves anything. Bank details go stale, records get harder to trace, and family memory fades.\nWhether you have a complete file or only scattered policy papers, Sahirasta can review the case and help identify the likely route to clarify or recover the unpaid survival benefit.\nRequest a Case Review"
    },
