      "Documents Usually Required": "The exact documents depend on the insurer, the policy stage, and whether the policyholder is alive or represented by family. Commonly relevant documents include:\nPolicy bond, policy number, premium receipts, payout intimation, claim communication, or any insurer record showing that an amount is due or pending release.\nPAN, Aadhaar, passport, address proof, overseas identity or address proof where relevant, and any other current KYC documents required for the policyholder or claimant.\nCancelled cheque, passbook copy, bank statement, banker certificate, closed-account proof, new-account proof, or any record showing failed or outdated payout routing.\nOld and current address or identity records where they help connect the present record with the historical policy file.\nDeath certificate, nominee proof, legal-heir papers, claimant identity documents, and entitlement support where the payout issue arises after the policyholder’s death.\nAny insurer letters, emails, SMS alerts, objection notes, branch communication, or servicing memos showing what mismatch or compliance issue the insurer has already flagged.",
      "Why These Cases Get Stuck": "These matters often drag on because the visible defect is only one part of the problem. A client may update the bank account but forget that PAN, address, or claimant identity still does not match the older file. The insurer then raises the next objection, and the client feels as though the goalpost keeps moving. In reality, the full record was never cleaned up together.\nAnother reason is that families often underestimate how much old insurance files depend on consistency. If the insurer sees one name on the policy, another on the bank record, an old address in the system, and incomplete KYC on the claimant side, the payout may remain stuck even where the policy itself is not in dispute.\nOlder LIC and insurer cases are especially prone to this because the record may have moved through paper servicing, branch transfers, manual updates, partial digitisation, and later compliance checks. By the time a payout is pursued seriously, several small defects may be sitting on top of each other.\nThese cases also become frustrating because the insurer may describe them as routine servicing matters, while the family experiences them as a near-complete block. That mismatch in perception is exactly why the file needs to be diagnosed properly instead of updated in fragments.",
      "Special Notes for Widows, Legal Heirs, and NRIs": "Widows and family members often encounter this problem at the worst possible stage: after they have already done the emotional and documentary work of identifying the policy and pursuing the claim, only to be told that the payout still cannot be released because the servicing record or banking route is not in order.\nLegal heirs may face a double burden where the policyholder’s old record was already outdated before death and the claimant now has to regularise both entitlement and payout details together. In such cases the file has to be built more carefully than a simple update request.\nNRIs face the additional complexity of linking current overseas identity, address, and banking or remittance-related records with an old Indian insurance file. These cases are often workable, but only if the sequence of corrections is handled with discipline and the insurer’s queries are addressed coherently.",
      "Frequently Asked Questions": "What does it mean when an insurer says payout is blocked because of KYC or bank mismatch?\nIt usually means the insurer is not satisfied that the amount can be safely released on the basis of the current banking and identity records available in the file.\nCan an old closed bank account stop insurance money from being released?\nYes. If the insurer is still holding outdated payout instructions, the release can fail or remain pending until the correct bank route is regularised properly.\nWhat if I already submitted new bank details but the insurer is still objecting?\nThat often means the problem is broader than one bank change. PAN, address, claimant identity, or other linked records may still not align with the old policy file.\nCan widows or legal heirs handle payout-blockage issues after the policyholder’s death?\nOften yes, but the file may need both entitlement proof and record-regularisation support before the insurer will release the amount.\nCan NRIs fix insurer KYC or bank-record issues without repeated travel?\nMany cases can be worked remotely, though older files usually need more careful document coordination and clearer sequencing than routine servicing requests.",
